In Java, when creating the BigDecimal, it's possible that the division countOdd/input is done precisely, but in Fortran, when we do dble(countOdd)/input, since both are double precision, then that's fine. Wait but the original Java code did:

BigDecimal result = new BigDecimal(countOdd / input);

Wait countOdd is double here. So in Fortran, countOdd is integer, but converted to double precision via dble( ) so yeah, that's the same. Now the Java's BigDecimal is using setScale, which rounds to 10 decimal digits.
